author: @theteacher3163
text: Dunno who is gonna read this, but I'll share my real personal experience I've had with this movie. I remember this trailer coming out. I was at the lowest point in my life, thinking about s**de and had no will to continue trying fixing my life and pulling myself together. I remember texting my friend about these thoughts and him being really worried about me and his constant signs of concern. He was really trying to help which I'm thankful to him for. Then this trailer came out and suddenly I realized that I really really needed to see this movie and how could I see it if I ended everything back then? So, I told myself that I would try my best to live the following 6 months before the movie premier and that I would go and watch this movie and have amazing time. And I did. I went to see that movie with my friends whom I really appreciate and thankful for being there for me. And I thank you, D&W, for keeping me alive and giving me a small goal to live for. By the time I watched the movie I had already put my life together. I'd fixed my schedule, started going to the gym, quit the job I hated, been much more open to my family and it's just feels amazing now. I doubt that Ryan or anyone else who's been behind of making this movie will read this, but nonetheless, THANK YOU. U really did save my life!

author: @DaviRoutner
text:
Rewatching Deadpool 3, or as many call it, â€œDeadpool and Wolverine,â€ makes it clear that the film is essentially an exaggerated egotrip by Ryan Reynolds. The actor, producer, writer, presenter, entrepreneur, and comedian seems to use the film as a personal showcase, saturating every scene with his extremely forced persona.

The first movie of the franchise is acceptable, the second one starts to get tiring, but the third provokes deep antipathyâ€”not so much toward the character, but toward the actor. Reynolds pushes his irreverence to the limit, turning the film into an egocentric indulgence where he delights in himself.

The plot is chaotic and seems to exist only to make room for an endless string of jokes. The storyline takes a back seat so that Deadpoolâ€™s character can monopolize the screen with shallow sarcasms that add nothing new. The presence of other iconic characters feels like nothing more than an excuse to boost Reynoldsâ€™ personal show, as if the movie were an awkward fanfic where he is the absolute protagonist.

Hugh Jackmanâ€™s return as Wolverine seems like a marketing ploy to attract audiences, but in the end, viewers are met with endless dialogues of inflated ego. What could have been an interesting interaction is lost in forced, unsubstantial lines.

In short, Deadpool 3 is a dull, tiresome, and pretentious film. Little entertainment, lots of irrelevance, and, above all, too much Ryan Reynolds. If I had to rate it, it would be a 3.5/10. Itâ€™s not a film worth watching more than once.

author: @elainegmorrison
text:
I fell asleep, then I wish I had stayed there. That running Deadpool speech is tiresome. I just don't get this talky movie. Maybe if I had been 12, and allowed to watch it if not for all the vulgar language. It had some interesting action scenes but the music choices were strange and they chopped up the movie in between the never-ending rambling about nothing with that whiny irritating voice from an actor who is often brilliant. Maybe it was written during the writers' strike. Why? Why?
I just thought of one thing which could have helped as I was at a complete loss earlier. Maybe choose a great song as a theme (it's hackneyed but the idea is coming...) and that becomes a running joke. When the character gives the line and the look we know the theme song is coming. Another character can even give an "oh brother, not again" expression. And when the character is revved up for a fight and the music starts someone else can direct him "not now" and the music cuts. Or the character searching for identity and greatness can search for a theme song and the other characters can critique it. "You actually hear that? I thought it was in my head", "Of course I can hear it. I'm not deaf and your music choices are disturbing" kind of thing.
Maybe since the movie was so talky the dialogue could be really high level meaning of life philosophy. And the characters would be on the move instead of standing around arguing. It doesn't have to be linear and real. They could be walking on a different plane of existence while having these esoteric conversations and you'd have to get some experts to give you the material. It's a movie and it's not real anyway so you can suspend the reality even more to make it interesting. Often the best innovation, the aha moment, comes from pulling rabbits out of hats to fix a problem.

IT'S A VERY DISSAPOINTNG A AWFUL MOVIE , I wacthed a few hours ago, omg, what a horrible introduction, it was quite hard to understand why Deadpoo was looking for Logan and why and what happeded to the world.

The movie is extremely boring and has a very pity action, the plot and the script , the narrive or storytelling , the context are a mess, poor and added randomly, I wasn't able interesting things from both characters who of course were not explored or developed during the movie.

The whole movie itself is a chaos, it wasn't well structured, defineed , contextualized and well plot , with different scenarios



The fights with enemies are too short obvious and boring, the humor is basically always the same, just references and offenses.

The enemy has/had no flashbacks or explanations of her origins, I was like wtf how can you introduce an enemy that way ?.

It is like teaching kids without words or vocab, it was a total deception.




I really deel disappointed, but well, I hope they can improve the way they make movies much better, with better trills, concepts, characters, flashbacks of the enemies and much better introductions rather than danding bye bye bye from NSYnc , I am pretty sure that a good intro about what happened to the world, to the people, and the importance of saving humanity through something explained elaborately could have been better by far.

author: @abishai619
text: I saw this Movie yesterday PARENTS BEWARE Let me be clear I am a Superhero Fan and have enjoyed the Deadpool series to this point. Good vs Evil where Good always wins is heart felt. This bastardization of that theme was gratuitously raunchy filled with way too many sexual innuendos. Granted its was funny when injected sparingly but this was over the top. Parents should know this is non stop lude and lascivious behavior. Add to that non stop killing beyond what you would see in a Horror Film granted excellent special effects awesome CGI but again gratuitous over the top non stop killing. It was as if on purpose to illustrate how absurd movies of this type are. A satire of sort's. I felt bad for the parents who brought their children to see it. I actually saw a group get up and leave. IMHO it is a sad day when someone thinks this is Family entertainment. I know I know I understand the ratings system an "R' means don't take kids but we all know that is sometimes ignored and Deadpool/Superhero movies are some of those many would. Bottom line this is a Stag Party movie shame on Disney for abusing there persona. I've resisted canceling them in the past but as much as I hate doing it they are dead to me now.

author: @fomobull4187
text:
Do not waste your money, this is literally the worst movie I have ever watched, I felt like leaving early but I thought it would be awkward. I have never watched these X-men before. It looks like you are supposed to watch the old movies first. I expected a superhero movie like Batman or Superman. But it is actually a comedy movie that parodies itself. They do not bother to explain what the multiverse is or any of the backstory. The movie is loaded with references to past movies in this series, none of which make sense. The actors speak into the camera and speak directly to the viewers and take jabs at rival movie studios, very meta. That was mildly fun, like, haha, ok, whatever.

I am uncertain if the movie had a story. I struggled not to fall asleep at one point. Something about preventing the destruction of a universe. The path to the ending seemed to be a string of comedy sketches that were not well connected. I guess the fan base must be in their 40s because they played a few old 80s hits for no good reason.

This series seems to have a fan base of sorts. Don't kill me, this is just how I experienced the movie.

author: @arpitsinghthakur1997
text:
Spoilers ahead.

1.) The timeline in some Marvel films is incorrect. Like in the movie Deadpool 2, when Deadpool goes to Xavier Mansion, we are shown the younger form of Charles Xavier, Quick Silver, Beast, Cylops in a room, the same form which was shown to us in X-Men Apocalypse, Dark Phoenix i.e. the year 1983. But in the movie Deadpool 2, the year 2018 is going on.

2.) The year 2023 is shown in X-Men Days of Future Past and the year 2029 in Logan. So have Professor X and Logan become so old in just 6 years? In Deadpool 3, Deadpool tells Wolverine that you are very respected in my world. You was the X-Man, you was the main X-Man, The Wolverine. Was...means Wolverine is dead now. In Deadpool 3, the year is 2024, so Logan will die after 5 years.


Marvel is confused about timeline.

author: @snaketooth0943
text:
For me, the movie is either a 8/10 or a 9/10. The humour and soundtrack were great... but, if I had to criticize anything, I would say I wished there were more MCU cameos, (but I guess I'm just a greedy MCU fan) some of the side characters were a bit 2-dimensional, but, even then, the main characters were pretty good. Oh, and the special effects and acting were good and the emotional moments were decent.

So, yeah, if you liked or loved the first 2 Deadpool movies and the other marvel movies, I'd say go see this. Oh, and make sure you've seen the first season of Loki... that got referenced quite a bit.

text:
Deadpool and Wolverine: A Fun Review and Commentary ğŸ¬ğŸ˜‚

Let's talk about Deadpool and Wolverine being in the same movie! I watched the trailer for "Deadpool and Wolverine: Together," and having these two characters on screen together promises to deliver all kinds of comedy and action explosions. Now, let's have some fun with this review, shall we? ğŸ˜‚

Deadpool: The Talkative Superhero ğŸ—£ï¸ğŸ’¥

What does Deadpool do? The guy cracks jokes in every scene, his style is legendary. Imagine Mike from your local coffee shop sitting down next to Deadpool and saying, "Man, you talk too much, give it a rest and have some coffee." ğŸ˜‚ When Deadpool's humor meets our everyday banter, laughter is guaranteed!

Wolverine: Grumpy but Charismatic ğŸºğŸ¦¸â€â™‚ï¸

Wolverine, on the other hand, is the ultimate grump, but also incredibly charismatic. This guy has claws and every fight scene is him basically saying, "Mess with me and you'll get hurt." Picture Jake from your local gym watching Wolverine and saying, "This guy is a total badass!" ğŸ˜‚ Grumpy yet charismatic, a perfect blend for an action hero.

Dynamic Duo: Contrast and Harmony ğŸ­ğŸ¤

What happens when these two come together? Deadpool keeps talking, and Wolverine just gives him that grumpy look. But it's exactly this contrast that creates their unique harmony. Imagine putting Chatty Mike and Grumpy Jake in the same taxi; they'd probably keep bantering all the way to infinity. That's exactly the kind of energy Deadpool and Wolverine bring! ğŸ¬ğŸ˜‚

Positive Aspects ğŸŒŸğŸ‰

- *Humor and Comedy:* Deadpool's endless jokes paired with Wolverine's silent but impactful presence will have the audience in stitches. This film promises a laughter-filled adventure.
- *Action:* Wolverineâ€™s intense action scenes combined with Deadpoolâ€™s absurd fighting techniques will deliver an adrenaline rush on screen.

Negative Aspects ğŸ˜’ğŸ§

- *Constant Jokes:* Deadpoolâ€™s non-stop humor might tire some viewers. "Can you be serious for a second, man?" might cross some minds. ğŸ˜‚
- *Mixed Tone:* The filmâ€™s tone might oscillate between extremely funny and very serious, which could leave some viewers feeling a bit confused.

Overall Expectations ğŸ¥ğŸ¿

As movie lovers, we'll watch this film and both laugh and get thrilled by the action. With Deadpoolâ€™s humor and Wolverineâ€™s toughness, this movie looks like a visual feast. After watching the trailer, I can confidently say, this movie is a must-watch!

Conclusion ğŸ¬ğŸ‰

In conclusion, "Deadpool and Wolverine: Together" promises to be a total package of fun and action. Weâ€™ll laugh, weâ€™ll be thrilled, and weâ€™ll have a great time. Letâ€™s wait and see if it meets our expectations. Looking forward to your comments! ğŸ¬ğŸ˜‚

author: @VigilanteVegan
text:
Maybe Iâ€™m in the minority here, but Iâ€™ll say it. Just because Sony, Fox, and Disney are three separate movie studios, does NOT mean the in-story explanation has to be that the characters in the respective three are in their own distinct universe.

Case in point, I thought the post-credit Venom scene in No Way Home was unnecessary, as thereâ€™s no reason for Sony to put themselves in that hole rather than have the implication that Tom Hollandâ€™s Spider-man is somewhere out there in that world, just offscreen & not referenced.

That being said, just because MCU acquired the rights to Deadpool, does NOT mean there needs to be in-story explanation of him traveling from Fox-verse to Marvel-verse and bringing Wolverine with him through a portal. Iâ€™m all for him referencing it breaking the fourth wall, but actually doing it as a major part of the plot is another story.

The most grounded way of doing it is to imply the X-men, Deadpool, and Wolverine have been in the same world alongside other Marvel characters all along. Just because past X-men instalments didnâ€™t reference them before, thatâ€™s perfectly fine.

The idea of characters switching universes because they change movie studios is absurd and unnecessary. The early Jason movies were distributed by Paramount. Then it switched to New Line Cinema. They never showed Jason hopping into a New Line portal so he could fight Freddy Krueger. ğŸ˜‚

Iâ€™m tired of multiverse stories. Theyâ€™re great every vicennium as a nostalgic treat, but as a plot device for every other movie, they must go. They make the writerâ€™s job very easy because theyâ€™re are infinite possibilities. There are no real threats and stake because a character can hop on over to Fox-verse and nab an alternate version of someone who just died. Iron Manâ€™s death has no meaning really since they can nab a new one over in Sony-verse who happens to look like Tom Cruise. Nothing matters.

Now, compare to a story like in â€œThe Batmanâ€ which has a grounded story without portals and potions to fill a 3-hour runtime where real things are at stake. When people die they die. These stories are harder to write. As I said, the multiverse can be fun, but it needs to go as a plot device. Ever since No Way Home, itâ€™s being used too much.

author: @cabellero1120
text:
The producers waited too long to make another sequel.
Six years...

Reynolds has stated this is his last time as DP.

The First 2 movies did something different, a super hero film that went its own way, outside of the " hero trope" box....

This film seems to conform to the same trope formula it was rebelling against...

Deadpool didn't need a " side kick" or Any help.

He didn't need or want to join the X Men!

Deadpool with Hulk or Captain America would have been bigger!

Deadpool vs Venom or Morbius would have been cool..

Why DP and Wolverine??

Anyway, I probably won't pay to see this since it will be on demand by mid summer.

author: @Okazu84
text:
And that was me disqualifying, cancelling, wiping away, de-indexing, closing, ignoring, yelling, yawning at every single suggestion of that trailer as yet another quality fan-made trailer, believing Jackman was (sadly) a man of his word when it came to Logan's ultimate fate in the film of the same name, that happened to be one of the most disturbing, obscure and mature iterations of the franchise's darkest timeline yet.

And then, I watched. And my mind exploded. Texting and sending frenetic audios to all my fan friends that laugh back at me since I'm SO late to the party.

I clicked on this trailer posted on a non-official channel believing I would at least enjoy a quality artist view of what "could have been in another Earth". I dreamed, hoped, waiting, thought, obsessed so many times, in so many forms, for so many years, randomly googling any piece of news that could have the slightest connection to such a revival that I had somehow completely made peace with leaving the most glorious past where it belonged, behind us, with our best memories to cherish about it.

And suddenly, the OFFICIAL Wolverine jumped, roared, swore, drank, was such a marvelous piece of tortured trash again and then shined on the savage battlefied, with non other than Reynold's Deadpool.

This cannot be real.

Yet, it is.

I , LOVE, MY, SILLY, DAY.

text: This is simply everything fans ever wanted. It only took (checks watch) how many decades? Give it up for Hugh, the man is 55-years-old and still looks ridiculously amazing as Wolverine. I will gladly watch Ryan Reynolds subvert every possible film rating and studio notes, for however long he wants to play Deadpool. Given the tech these days, he could easily do it for another 20 - 30 years, and I'd have no problem with that. Then again, he seems to be the only one who gets comic fans, and he'd be my Board Vote to lead a studio any day. He's proven he can do it. Take my money, Ryan, any day, it's always entertaining, and that's all we want.

text:
It looks like Cassandra Nova may be portrayed accurately to her comic source, which I'll be very happy with.

Alioth appearing makes me wonder if he's the greater threat of the story while Cassandra Nova is the main focused villain. Either way, I'm intrigued.

"You were THE X-Man." Well to a certain nostalgic crowd sure, but there's a lot of other X-Men fans would personally call other X-Men "THE X-Man. But that's a whole flame war nobody really wants to get into I'm sure.

Looks like they'll be using some "Old Man Logan" story elements for this one. Giant Dead Ant-Man being a clear reference to "Pym Falls".

author: @WednesdayAddams-X
text: OK so here are my speculations. Based on both trailers, we see Deadpool approaching a Wolverine dressed up as "patch" in the first trailer, and then in this one we see him approaching Wolverine in a bar (possibly for the first time) so I'm thinking that at least 2 different Wolverines (Variants) confirmed. The TVA recruits Deadpool because of his healing factor and his fighting skills because they are AFRAID of approaching any Wolverine variants to capture them (for whatever reason) so they need Deadpool's help with that because he's the only one who can do it (fight a Wolverine variant and survive), now I'm expecting that the TVA tricks Deadpool because we see him killing TVA agents in the trailer so they either lie to him about why they want these Wolverine variants captured/pruned, or he just discovers something he doesn't like right after he succeeds in capturing Wolverine because we see him lying on the ground so either way Deadpool ends up turning against them but he and this Wolverine get pruned as well and get sent to the Void at the end of time (where we see the 20th century fox logo) because we also see Alioth (the cloudy looking creature) in the trailer which we saw for the first time in the LOKI series. Now we also hear Deadpool saying ("I'm about to lose everything that I ever cared about" and "I don't know anything about saving worlds") and I did say earlier that he discovers something he doesn't like so that could be that he discovers that the TVA wants to prune/erase his reality (Deadpool's reality)!! So that means Vanessa, Dopinder, Al, and all the others that we see in the trailer will be gone forever and it's possibly because in his last movie Deadpool went back in time to save Vanessa (which is something that he's not supposed to do based on how the TVA works) so Deadpool starts to try and convince Wolverine to help him save his world (giving him a chance for redemption for failing to save his own) as well as finding a way to get out of the void and back to the TVA to stop them in time. I don't know if the Dr. Strange portal has anything to do with getting them out or not but they will be encountering lots of characters along the way possibly other variants. But the real villain here is the TVA. At least that's what I think, but I could be wrong though. Either way I think at least some of it is real based on what the trailer shows. At least some of it makes sense. Don't you agree?

text:
Noticed:

- Wolverine in a bar again with a rude bartender, just like X-Men 1
- Claw trouble again, like in Logan
- "Go f*** yourself." (like X-Men: First Class)
- Alioth. {Where's Renslayer?)
- Pretty sure the Giant-Man head is a jab at Quantumania.
- Toad, Lady Deathstrike, Azazel, Callisto? Probably bound to be a lot more surprises in the movie, so Marvel's only showing us a few crumbs before the meal.
- Motorcycle chariot? Seems like this production shares crew from Furiosa.
- The inclusion of "Like a Prayer" is possibly more important than it seems. The background behind it might be dazzling.

text:
Fun trailer, enough (hopefully practical) FX and the core cast have the right kind of chemistry (blood and white powder, or the implication thereof). What it's missing so far is the Adamantium blades and dual swords doing more than poking actions, i want to see bits missing off the maniacs mauled by the duo.
DON'T screw this franchise up marvel/disney, i'm already sick of the bait n switches, MASSIVE jump off a cliff in quality/writing/overarching-plot and the forced introduction of failed-run characters in famous/popular characters' movies/shows/storylines for that new person to steal all the limelight and kill-steal the final encounter.

NO LAST MINUTE ROSTER SWAPS in the final act.

author: @nateborie6329
text:
Two things:
1.) THANK YOU DISNEY! You have officially grown up and allowed something like this to rear its beautiful head. Absolutely perfect. It doesn't feel like a single beat of comedy is missed, and seeing Jackman and Reynolds together like this is absolutely perfect.
2.) I love the design for Logan's claws. I'm going to keep commenting on them. That partial dull blade tip, and the deeper shade of silver is just epic. And it looks like Jackman has barely stepped away from the role of Wolverine. You can take the Jackman away from the animal, but you can't take the animal away from the Jackman, and I can already see myself dying of laughter when this comes out.

author: @Palmieres
text:
Okay. I collected comics for a long time. I never thought the movie adaptations were even close to decent. But Hugh Jackman has just become Wolverine for me right now. His age has been a benefit to this portrayal, because Wolverine is old , and while Jackman isn't as old, this right here is what Wolverine is supposed to look like. Now, I loved the character in "Logan", but that is not the same "golden age of the 90s" character, that's someone different, made difference by even more time and trauma. That's a little diamond of a movie in the middle of mediocrity.
But this guy right here... this is just right.
